title: Protests in Egypt
name: Protests in Egypt
description: Though not all of these locations can be independently verified, there have been reports of protests at some of these locations around Egypt. Other sites on here are for reference.

properties.name: Tahrir Square
properties.description: Protests continued in Tahrir Square Sunday, and opposition candidate Mohammed ElBaradei addressed the crowd, demanding an end to the Mubarak regime.

properties.name: The Pyramids
properties.description: Protests have threatened Egypt's tourism industry. The pyramids have been closed for protection.

properties.name: Maadi
properties.description: ABC reports that the Egyptian Army has set up checkpoints in Maadi, trying to prevent prison escapes. Maadi has been the site of violent clashes this week.

properties.name: Alexandria
properties.description: Protests continue in Alexandria, with injury and death tolls rising and hospitals crowded. Al-Masry Al-Youm English reports that at least eight police stations have been set on fire and CBC reports that government buildings have been targeted as well and the military deployed - moved welcomed by protestors.

properties.name: The Egyptian Museum
properties.description: Looters have hit the Egyptian Museum in the unrest, reportedly breaking several mummies.

properties.name: NDP Headquarters
properties.description: Protestors set the ruling National Democratic Party headquarters on fire.

properties.name: Ramses Square
properties.description: Al-Masry Al-Youm English reported that protestors demonstrated in Ramses Wquare, circumventing police who were trying to block entrance to downtown.

properties.name: Suez
properties.description: Suez has seen some of the most violent clashes during the unrest. There have been protests at the morgues and jails.

properties.name: Mahalla
properties.description: Mahalla, the site of the 2008 riots has seen large protests in recent days.

properties.name: Sharm el-Sheikh
properties.description: In Sharm el-Skeikh Al-Jazeera is reporting that the military has been deployed into the city, and tourists in the resort town have reported that barricades and checkpoints have been put up around many hotels. Otherwise the city has been reported as calm with no sense of the crisis. The nearby Suez Canal will reportedly remain unaffected by protests as Bloomberg reported, and Suez Canal Authority officials have assured there will be no interruptions.

properties.name: Mansoura
properties.description: Clashes have been reported in Mansoura as the city joined the widespread anti-Mubarak protests.

properties.name: Ismailia
properties.description: Thousands of people took to the streets in Ismailia, according to an independent Egyptian daily newspaper, five protesters were reported killed after clashes with police, though those numbers cannot be independently verified.

properties.name: El Arish
properties.description: The Egyptian government deployed more forces to its border region, according to Israeli Brigadier-General Tzvika Foghel, a Palestinian wire service reported.

properties.name: Rafah
properties.description: A group of protesters on Saturday attacked state security headquarters in the town of Rafah near Egypt's border with Israel, killing three policemen, Reuters reported.
